She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and it surprised me," he said to The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains how important it is for good sleep habits to be able to perform academically and sportingly, and for the general state.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and adm. dir. for the university's health services, said that the university decided to start the course after they saw that the students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for one hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one part there is a picture of a room in a dormitory, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, jogging shoes and books and learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important it is with a sleep routine.
