The app uses Solid technology to let people create their own ‘personal online repository’ or a POD.
It may include contact lists, work lists, calendars, music libraries and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify all are available on one browser at a time.
What's unique about the online personal repository is that it's up to the user who should have access to that kind of information.
The company calls it ‘personal authorisation through data’.
The idea behind Inrupt is, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, that the company should provide resources, process and relevant competence to make Solid available to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some leased-in developers on contract to work with the project and a bunch of volunteer programmers.
From this week on, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to «Facebook and Google that they are going to introduce something completely new or not, which will make their business models completely recalibrated overnight.
‘We do not request their permission’.
In an article on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupts’ mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps to protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid."
In 1994 Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he established the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an important voice in the debate on online neutrality.
Although he launches Inrupt, Berners-Lee will still be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute.
‘I’m incredibly optimistic about the next epoch of the web’, added Berners-Lee.
