The study for researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brown-and-water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be located at important locations around the property to track seasonal bat activity.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also perform mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
The sound analyses of all recordings by experts will determine the frequency of the bats and the species that do.
A habitat map and a report will then be prepared to provide a detailed landscape view of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation consultant, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will form part of the decision on the measures to be taken, such as the installation of pastures and the best management of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has fallen considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction affecting breeding grounds and habitat restriction.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials and attacks from Huskats.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes for catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and roadblocks when they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have 10 competent experts who regularly conduct studies, breeding sites and rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only own bat reserve at Threave Landingdom in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
