Algal bloom update: concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Commission for Fisheries and Animal Life (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spotted blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County — suggesting reduced concentrations.
A red algae bloom stretches about 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
It detects spots about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer sites than last week.
Rødalger has also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County have been reported in the last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
Irritation is still reported in the respiratory tracts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
No irritation was reported in the northwest of Florida during the past week.
